{{Underlinked|date=August 2015}}

'''Simonet Biokou''' is a Beninois Vodou artist. Based in [[Porto Novo]], [[Benin]], where Vodou (or [[West African Vodun|Voodoo]]) is an official religion practiced by 40% of the population.

Before starting work each morning he sings to a statue of god Gu.<ref name="Beaujean-Baltzer2009">{{cite book|last=Beaujean-Baltzer|first=Gaëlle|title=Artistes d'Abomey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AnNJAQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Musée du quai Branly|page=127}}</ref> He is noted for his work using scrap metals, including the rims of wheels and bicycle chains, bolts and springs, which he uses mainly to make metal works of Voodoo gods.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jeune Afrique L'intelligent|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zMkVAQAAIAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Groupe Jeune Afrique|page=105}}</ref><ref name="AuziasLabourdette2010">{{cite book|last1=Auzias|first1=Dominique|last2=Labourdette|first2=Jean-Paul|title=Bénin 2011|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8x2RbmpD67IC&pg=PA51|date=1 October 2010|publisher=Petit Futé|language=French|isbn=2-7469-2924-4|page=51}}</ref>

The artist has frequently exhibited in Africa, Europe and Canada. He is the only African Biokou sculptor exhibited at the Contemporary Art Museum of Liège.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.beninartsvisuels.org/repertoire/artiste/Ou%C3%A9m%C3%A9/biokou-simonet-biokou|title = Biokou|date = |accessdate = 19 October 2015|website = Benin Arts Visuels|publisher = |last = Badoi|first = Fabiola}}</ref>

Biokou played himself in the 1998 film Divine carcasse.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0155674/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_1|title = Divine carcasse|date = |accessdate = 19 October 2015|website = IMDb|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>

